<paragraph blockId="57.[151,1059,1344,1425]" pageId="57" pageNumber="1016">
D i a g n o s i s: The extraordinarily rough punctation on the pronotal disc will distinguish the members of this species from congeners. The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1950" box="[846,970,1374,1395]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="57" pageNumber="1019" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[846,970,1374,1395]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="1016">Pujoliclerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
PIC was revised in 2014 (
<bibRefCitation author="OPITZ W" box="[321,457,1403,1425]" pageId="57" pageNumber="1016" pagination="727 - 756" refId="ref53564" refString="OPITZ W. (2014 d): Classification, natural history, and evolution of the checkered beetle genus Pujoliclerus PIC (Coleoptera: Cleridae: Peloniinae). - The Coleopteristss Bulletin 68 (4): 727 - 756." type="journal article" year="2014">OPITZ 2014d</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="57.[151,1059,1441,1583]" lastBlockId="58.[151,1059,212,353]" lastPageId="58" lastPageNumber="1017" pageId="57" pageNumber="1016">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 
<quantity box="[516,597,1441,1463]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="57" pageNumber="1016" unit="mm" value="4.5">4.5 mm</quantity>
; width 
<quantity box="[673,753,1441,1463]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="57" pageNumber="1016" unit="mm" value="1.7">1.7 mm</quantity>
. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[895,980,1441,1463]" captionStart="Figs 346-349" captionStartId="114.[151,191,1496,1518]" captionTargetBox="[151,1058,195,1478]" captionTargetId="figure@114.[151,1059,195,1478]" captionTargetPageId="114" captionText="Figs 346-349: Habitus; (346) Pujoliclerus mexicoensis; (347) P. sentus; (348) P. testudinatus; (349) P. trunculus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746836" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746836/files/figure.png" pageId="57" pageNumber="1016">Fig. 347</figureCitation>
. Color: Cranium mostly testaceous, frons and epicranium black; antenna black; pterothorax and abdomen brown; elytra mostly brown, epipleural margin testaceous; legs mostly yellow, prothoracic tibiae brown; prothoracic and metathoracic tarsi brown, metathoracic tibiae yellow. Head: Cranium coarsely punctate; antenna (
<figureCitation box="[686,762,1561,1583]" captionStart="Figs 1-27" captionStartId="70.[151,191,1302,1324]" captionTargetBox="[155,1057,207,1268]" captionTargetId="figure@70.[155,1058,207,1283]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="Figs 1-27: Antennae; (1) Aphelocerus nodus; (2) A. copanus; (3) A. magnipannus; (4) A. yoro; (5) A. sparicapillus; (6) A. tigra. (7) A. nolus; (8) A. ligulus; (9) Perilypus schusteri; (10) P. apunctus; (11) P. virgulatus; (12) P. izabal; (13) P. alpinus; (14) Cregya fuscomacula; (15) Phonius versus; (16) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (17) Pelonium falcatum; (18) Pujoliclerus cnecostus; (19) P. trunculus. (20) P. sentus; (21) P. testudinatus; (22) P. catie; (23) P. flavidus; (24) P. convexus; (25) P. meloinus; (26) P. mexicoensis; (27) P. tuxtlas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746746/files/figure.png" pageId="57" pageNumber="1016">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
) capitate, funicular antenno- meres shorter to capitulum; capitular antennomeres 8 and 9 triangular, antennomere 10 ovoid; eyes large, coarsely facetted, eye as wide as frons (EW/FW 25/25). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[268,358,271,293]" captionStart="Figs 134-152" captionStartId="77.[151,191,1476,1498]" captionTargetBox="[183,1049,204,1454]" captionTargetId="figure@77.[152,1060,199,1462]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="Figs 134-152: Pronota; (134) Pujoliclerus catie; (135) P. mexicoensis; (136) P. convexus; (137) P. testudinatus; (138) Madoniella selvanegra; (139) Cregya entrerios; (140) Pujoliclerus trunculus; (141) P. sentus; (142) P. meloinus; (143) Sicamus suprus; (144) Nepsudia guenda; (145) Nanoclerus fuscus; (146) Topainca pachacutii; (147) Eurycaulis anaxeis; (148) Kataspinula puebla; (149) Madoniella muralla; (150) M. nota; (151) M. acicula; (152) M. baja." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746760" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746760/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="1017">Fig. 141</figureCitation>
) slightly transverse (PW/PL 80/73), disc coarsely punctate, lateral tubercles well developed; elytra sculptured with 10 striae of asetiferous punctures (EL/EW 190/55). Abdomen: Pygidium scutiform.
</paragraph>
